<h2>Readonly vs Disabled</h2>
<p>These two attributes look similar but behave very differently. Choosing the wrong one is a common source of bugs.</p>

<code-block language="html" label="Readonly vs disabled">{{ comparisonExample | escape }}</code-block>

<table>
  <thead><tr><th>Behavior</th><th><code>readonly</code></th><th><code>disabled</code></th></tr></thead>
  <tbody>
    <tr><td>User can edit</td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>User can focus/tab</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>User can select/copy text</td><td>Yes</td><td>Varies by browser</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Value submitted with form</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Constraint validation runs</td><td>No</td><td>No</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Visual appearance</td><td>Subtle (your CSS)</td><td>Grayed out</td></tr>
  </tbody>
</table>

<h2>Form Submission</h2>
<p>This is the primary reason to choose <code>readonly</code> over <code>disabled</code>. Readonly fields are included in <code>FormData</code> and submitted to the server.</p>

<code-block language="js" label="FormData includes readonly">{{ formDataExample | escape }}</code-block>

<h2>Elements That Ignore readonly</h2>
<p>The <code>readonly</code> attribute only works on text-like inputs and <code>&lt;textarea&gt;</code>. It has <strong>no effect</strong> on:</p>
<ul>
  <li><code>&lt;select&gt;</code> — the user can still change the selection</li>
  <li><code>&lt;input type="checkbox"&gt;</code> — the user can still toggle it</li>
  <li><code>&lt;input type="radio"&gt;</code> — the user can still change the selection</li>
  <li><code>&lt;input type="range"&gt;</code> — the slider is still draggable</li>
  <li><code>&lt;input type="color"&gt;</code> — the picker still opens</li>
</ul>

<code-block language="html" label="Readonly does not work on select">{{ selectNotWorkExample | escape }}</code-block>

<p>For these elements, use <code>disabled</code> paired with a <code>&lt;input type="hidden"&gt;</code> to carry the value, or use JavaScript to prevent changes.</p>

<h2>Styling</h2>
<p>Use the <code>:read-only</code> and <code>:read-write</code> pseudo-classes to style readonly fields distinctly from editable ones.</p>

<code-block language="css" label="Readonly styling">{{ cssExample | escape }}</code-block>

<p><strong>Note:</strong> The <code>:read-only</code> pseudo-class also matches elements that are not editable by nature (like <code>&lt;p&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;div&gt;</code>). For precise targeting, combine it with an element selector: <code>input:read-only</code>.</p>

<h2>JavaScript API</h2>
<p>The <code>readOnly</code> property (camelCase) reflects the attribute.</p>

